results.output_text:
The enthalpy change at absolute zero (ΔH$_{\text{f}}$) for a molecule (M) can be calculated using the sum of its single-particle energy (ESP) and zero-point energy (ZPE), subtracted by the collective energy contribution from its constituent atoms (A) and their respective enthalpy changes at 0 K. This thermodynamic relation is expressed mathematically as:

\begin{equation}
\Delta H_{\text{f}}(M, 0\, \text{K}) = \text{ESP}^M + \text{ZPE}^M - \sum_{A \in M} (\text{ACE} - \Delta H_{\text{f}}(A, 0\, \text{K}))
\end{equation}

In simpler terms, the heat absorbed or released by M at absolute temperature is derived from its own ground state energy plus vibrational energy, minus the combined energy of A's contribution and their corresponding enthalpy changes at absolute zero. The formulation ensures a comprehensive and precise description of energy transformations in chemical systems.

